Extracting elevation data using the ‘elevatr’ package

Aditya Ranganath

3/16/2022

library(tmap)
library(elevatr)
library(raster)
library(sf)
library(tidycensus)
library(tidyverse)

1 Generating elevation rasters using “elevatr”

CO_polygon<-get_decennial(geography = "state", 
                          variables = "P001001",
                          year = 2010,
                          geometry=TRUE) %>% 
                    filter(NAME=="Colorado")
tm_shape(CO_polygon)+
  tm_polygons()

co_elevation<-get_elev_raster(locations=CO_polygon, proj=CO_polygon, z=9, clip="locations")
## Mosaicing & Projecting
## Clipping DEM to locations
## Note: Elevation units are in meters.
co_elevation
## class      : RasterLayer 
## dimensions : 3186, 5575, 17761950  (nrow, ncol, ncell)
## resolution : 0.001259004, 0.001259004  (x, y)
## extent     : -109.0605, -102.0416, 36.99253, 41.00372  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## crs        : +proj=longlat +datum=NAD83 +no_defs 
## source     : memory
## names      : file12d1279fe2d7f 
## values     : 1012, 4466  (min, max)
CO_elevation_map<-tm_shape(co_elevation)+
                      tm_raster(title="Elevation in Colorado (m)")+
                      tm_legend(outside=T)
CO_elevation_map
## stars object downsampled to 1323 by 756 cells. See tm_shape manual (argument raster.downsample)

2 Extracting elevations at points

CO_points<-st_sample(CO_polygon, 20, type="random")
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
CO_elevation_map+
tm_shape(CO_points)+
  tm_dots()
## stars object downsampled to 1323 by 756 cells. See tm_shape manual (argument raster.downsample)

get_elev_point(locations=CO_points, proj=CO_points, src="aws")
